Observation Details: We were able to get extraordinarily close to two PB grebes trapped in a semicircle of liquid water in an otherwise frozen section of pond.  They kept diving then popping right back up in a panicked manner (uncharacteristically briefly, mere seconds, subsurface for a species that can clearly hold its breath rather well underwater).  They somehow knew they could find no other place to surface had they tried to evade us under the ice, thin as it was.   -- Opportunistic photos to follow...

Media notes: All 4 chicks riding high on parent's back.
Observation Details: Very quiet here during this time re: other birds but it was thrilling to watch a PB Grebe family of 6!! Another young one must have hatched since our last record as there are now 4. Lots of feeding going on....parents trade off carrying the chicks on their backs by "shaking" them off--that was cool to see! Also some independence starting to happen as one parent left two chicks in the water after they fed from Mom....the 2 little ones looked all around their fluid world for approx. 3 minutes [which is a long time to start with] then they paddled over to Dad and hopped on his back again. Not much room under those back feathers for all 4 growing chicks anymore!

Observation Details: We were able to get extraordinarily close to two PB grebes trapped in a semicircle of liquid water in an otherwise frozen section of pond. They somehow knew they could find no other place to surface had they tried to evade us under the ice, thin as it was.   -- Opportunistic photos to follow...
